No, just a realist, because once again I read the annual Social Security statement that arrived in the mail.
AdvertisementUnfortunately, time is running out for Social Security to be drastically reformed.
Meanwhile, the cost of Social Security is staggering as displayed on the U.S. Debt Clock.
(What I often refer to as the U.S. government’s “ticking time bomb.”)Today, Social Security is the government’s second-largest annual budget expense at $967.5 billion.
Remember, 2022 is still four years from the beginning of the “bulge years” that start in 2026, when Social Security costs will significantly escalate.